ōra</i> ‘ore’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Orrill","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire and Leicestershire): variant of   Orrell  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Orrell was born in 1275, in Newton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas de Orrell, was 13 and his mother, Mrs. Thomas de Orrell, was 15. He died in Market Harborough, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1275–":"1275–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1303–1353":"1303–1353","1307–1381":"1307–1381","–Male":"Surnud","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1302–1340":"1302–1340","1262–1330":"1262–1330","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1262":"1262","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1381":"1381","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1303